el","married_names":[],"display_name":"Shirley Mae Bonesteel Courage","gender":"female","photo_url":"https://res.cloudinary.com/dc5clrqtw/image/upload/v1780761077/36409982_2942c52f-2eeb-4c1d-a02f-9c6765f8f54c_cjxcr6.jpg"},"military_service":[],"slug":"shirley-mae-bonesteel-1926"},"TD0346":{"id":"TD0346","former_ids":[],"is_placeholder":false,"has_descendants_documented":false,"gender":"male","birth":{"year":1911,"month":11,"day":29,"city":"New York","state":"New York","country":"United States"},"classification":{"is_thomas_descendant":false,"is_talcott_descendant":true,"is_thomas_spouse":false,"is_talcott_spouse":false,"include_in_path_calculation":true,"descent_paths_to_thomas":0,"descent_from_thomas_hooker":false,"descent_from_john_talcott":true,"is_progenitor":false,"is_easter_egg":false,"generation_from_john_talcott":8},"notable":{"is_notable":false,"notable_category":[]},"parents":{"father_id":"TD0337","father_name":"Raphael Welles Pumpelly","mother_id":"I01543","mother_name":"Amelie Sybil Van Doren Ripley"},"number_of_marriages":2,"marriages":[{"spouse_id":"I01553","spouse_name":"Marta Marie Szalonek","marriage_year":1940,"children_ids":[],"notes":"Divorced 1942."},{"spouse_id":"I01554","spouse_name":"Shirley Mae Bonesteel","marriage_year":1949,"children_ids":[],"notes":"Four children; divorced 1980."}],"tags":[],"narrative_blocks":[{"category":"family","header":"He carried the family's Bahá'í faith forward","body":"Raphael Ripley Pumpelly, also styled Raphael Pumpelly III, was born in Manhattan in 1911 and took up the family's Bahá'í faith as his father had. He married twice and lived to ninety-four, dying in Los Angeles in 2006.","number":1},{"category":"character","header":"He lived a year in a mountain cave","body":"As a boy Raphael III spent about a year with his father and siblings in a cave on Mount Monadnock after the 1925 divorce. He later settled in California, where his second wife went on to marry a film composer.","number":2}],"sources":[],"institutions":[],"landmarks":[],"artworks":[],"research_tags":[],"cross_connections":[],"quotes":[],"research_sources":[],"documents":[],"statues":[],"bio":{"first_name":"Raphael Ripley","last_name":"Pumpelly","married_names":[],"display_name":"Raphael Ripley Pumpelly","gender":"male"},"military_service":[],"death":{"year":2006,"month":8,"day":19,"city":"Los Angeles","state":"California","country":"United States"},"slug":"raphael-ripley-pumpelly-1911"},"X03116":{"id":"X03116","former_ids":[],"is_placeholder":false,"has_descendants_documented":false,"gender":"male","birth":{"year":1919,"month":12,"day":10,"city":"Philadelphia","state":"Pennsylvania","country":"United States"},"death":{"year":2008,"month":5,"day":15,"city":"Pacific Palisades","state":"California","country":"United States"},"classification":{"is_thomas_descendant":false,"is_talcott_descendant":false,"is_thomas_spouse":false,"is_talcott_spouse":false,"include_in_path_calculation":false,"descent_paths_to_thomas":0,"descent_from_thomas_hooker":false,"descent_from_john_talcott":false,"is_progenitor":false,"is_easter_egg":false},"notable":{"is_notable":true,"notable_category":["arts"],"notable_blurb":"Composer of the Star Trek theme","primary_url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Alexander_Courage","primary_url_label":"Wikipedia"},"parents":{},"number_of_marriages":1,"marriages":[{"spouse_id":"I01554","spouse_name":"Shirley Mae Bonesteel","marriage_year":1980,"children_ids":[]}],"tags":[],"narrative_blocks":[{"category":"arts","header":"He wrote the Star Trek fanfare","body":"Hired at Jerry Goldsmith's suggestion, Alexander 'Sandy' Courage composed the soaring theme for the original Star Trek and several of its episode scores. The opening fanfare became one of the franchise's most enduring musical signatures.","number":1},{"category":"arts","header":"He made the Enterprise 'whoosh' himself","body":"When sound editors could not find the right effect, Courage produced the famous 'whoosh' of the Enterprise crossing the screen himself. He later fell out with Gene Roddenberry, who claimed half the theme's royalties by writing lyrics never meant to be sung.","number":2},{"category":"career","header":"He orchestrated for Williams, Previn, and Goldsmith","body":"At MGM and beyond, Courage orchestrated scores for André Previn, John Williams, and Jerry Goldsmith, on films from My Fair Lady to Superman. He arranged celebrated dance numbers in Seven Brides for Seven Brothers and Gigi.","number":3},{"category":"character","header":"A boyhood tune that foretold his career","body":"As a boy Courage taught himself to pick out songs from a show called The Band Wagon, with no idea what lay ahead. Years later he was writing arrangements for Fred Astaire in the film version of that very show.","number":4},{"category":"arts","header":"An Emmy, a camera, and fast cars","body":"Courage won a 1988 Emmy for music direction on a Julie Andrews Christmas special. A keen photographer and racing enthusiast, he counted the drivers Phil Hill and Stirling Moss among his friends.","number":5}],"sources":[],"institutions":[],"landmarks":[],"artworks":[],"research_tags":[],"cross_connections":[],"quotes":[],"research_sources":[],"documents":[],"statues":[],"bio":{"first_name":"Alexander","last_name":"Courage","married_names":[],"display_name":"Alexander \"Sandy\" Courage","gender":"male","photo_url":"https://res.cloudinary.com/dc5clrqtw/image/upload/v1780761150/27174790_d5ab367e-a45c-4013-8c14-1dbcf7466ecc_yauujn.jpg"},"military_service":[],"slug":"alexander-courage-1919"}},"burialCemetery":null,"institutionsById":{},"crossConnections":[]}